Traditional IT Deployment Models 
	• On Prem 
	• Colocation

On Prem : 
	• All equipment is located in your building
	• All equipment is owned by you 
	• Everything in the building is your responsibility and the connection between offices are your network service provider responsibility
	• Your equipment  is a Capital Expenditure cost
	• New equipment will typically take over a week to deploy
	• Equipment requires technology refreshes
	• You need to consider redundancy
	
	• Data Center Tiers
		○ Tier 1
			§ 99.671% Availability
			§ Annual downtime - 28.8 hours
		○ Tier 2
			§ 99.749% Availability
			§ Annual downtime - 22 hours
			§ One path of power and cooling
			§ Some redundancy in power
		○ Tier 3
			§ 99.982% Availability
			§ Annual downtime - 1.6 hours
			§ Multi power and cooling paths
			§ Fault tolerant (N+1)
			§ Need 4 generators
			§ Sustains 72 hours power outage
		○ Tier 4
			§ 99.995% Availability
			§ Annual downtime - .04 hours

Colocation :

	• A colocation center is a data center location where the owner of the facility rents out space to external customers
	• The facility owner provides power, cooling and physical security for their customer servers, storage and networking equipment
	• Independent colo providers such as Equinix offer customers multiple network connectivity options through a choice of network service provider
	• Network service providers will also typically peer with each other in colo facilities
	• Your server infrastructure is located in the external colo building
	• Your user desktops will still be in your offices
	• The colo provider owns the data center facilities and is responsible for providing highly available power, cooling and physical security according to the terms of the SLA
	• You own your own server , storage and networking equipment within the colo facility
	• The connection between your offices and the colo are your network service providers responsibility.
	• Your equipment within the colo facility is a Capital Expenditure cost
	• The monthly colo hosting fees are an Operational Expenditure
	• New equipment will typically take over a week to deploy
	• Equipment requires technology refreshes
	• You need to consider redundancy for the hardware you own, but power and cooling is handled by facility

